<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-11-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1474" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1474">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.55/42.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-11-24">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 24, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My November 17. Chinese merchants under order of arrest have taken out
                            writs of habeas corpus against the Government of Panama which have been
                            referred to the Supreme Court, thus directly testing constitutionality
                            of Law 50. Inventories completed. Chinese have opened shops. Situation
                            greatly relieved.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wicker</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>